                        <p style="font-size:100%;">
                            St. Thomas of Villanova was known for his great charity to the poor and marginalized. The Villanova community celebrates its patron saint and his legacy of Caritas – Love – with an annual Day of Service in his name.<br> </br>

Each year, the St. Thomas of Villanova Day of Service brings together nearly 5,000 students, faculty, staff, alumni and their families working in partnership with neighborhood agencies to perform service throughout Greater Philadelphia.<br> </br>
This annual event builds upon the great service performed throughout the year by the Villanova community and exists as a unique way to put its Augustinian ideals into action.<br> </br>

The Day of Service is part of the University’s St. Thomas of Villanova Celebration, honoring its patron saint – the 16th century Augustinian bishop of Valencia, Spain – known for his great charity to the poor and marginalized.<br> </br>
One of the largest single-day service events in the region, this annual event builds upon the service performed throughout the year by the Villanova community and exists as a unique way to put its Augustinian ideals into action.<br> </br>

“The St. Thomas of Villanova Celebration provides our community with a unique opportunity at the beginning of the academic year to celebrate our Augustinian mission and heritage,” said the Rev. Peter M. Donohue, OSA, PhD, Villanova University President.<br> </br>
“This year marks the 10th anniversary of this multi-day event and the widespread participation from all corners of the University—students, faculty, staff and alums—is a testament to the important role that service plays in the Villanova experience.<br> </br>
I am delighted that the Day of Service has become such a powerful demonstration of our community’s commitment to service.”
